 The hit/effect of farm credit in Pakistan 
 Shahidur R. Khandker*, Rashid R. Faruqee 1 
 The World Bank, 1818 H Street NW Washington, DC 20433, USA 
 
 Received 9 April2001; received in changed form 13 February 2002; accepted 22 July 2002 
 
 Abstract 
 Both informal and formal loans matter in farming. However, formal lenders provide many more production loans than 
 informal lenders, often at a cost (mostly loan default cost) higher than what they can recover. For example, the Farming-based 
 Development Bank of Pakistan (ADBP), providing about 90% of formal loans in areas away from cities, gets/causes high loan default costs. 
 Yet, like other governments, the Government of Pakistan supports the formal big plan/layout/dishonest plan on the grounds that lending to farming 
 is a high risk activity because of covariate risk. Because of this, such policies are often based on a market failure argument. As farm 
 credit big plans/layouts/dishonest plans are give money tod, policy makers must know if these big plans/layouts/dishonest plans are worth supporting. Using a recent large household 
 survey data from (away from cities) Pakistan ((away from cities) (money-related) Market Studies or RFMS), we have tried to guess the effectiveness 
 of the ADBP as a credit delivery institution. A two-stage method that takes the endogeneity of borrowing into account is 
 used to guess credit hit/effect. Results show/tell about that ADBP adds/gives to household welfare and that its hit/effect is higher for 
 smallholders than for large holders. Anyway, large holders receive most of ADBP finance. The ADBP is, this way, not a 
 (producing a lot for a given amount of money) institution in delivering (away from cities) finance. Its (producing a lot for a given amount of money)ness can be improved by reducing its loan default cost 
 and partially by targeting smallholders in farming where credit produces better results. 
