 (i) it is expensive; 3 (ii) it is (for only a short time) and mostly 
 used for eating/drinking; and (iii) it is not generally large 
 enough to cause/increase  investment and growth. 
 Not prevented by/not part of the issue the limits of informal finance, 
 many governments have tried in the past to develop different banks to provide credit 
 to farmers and other (away from cities) producers. Many such attempts have failed not only in delivering credit to target families but also in (helping increase/showing in a good way) a doable/possible credit 
 delivery system. High covariate risk of farming-based 
 production (Binswanger and Rosenzweig, 1986), the 
 not mirror-images information, lack of enforcement of loan 
 contracts (Hoff and Stiglitz, 1990),4 government unwise interference in credit markets, and rent-looking (for) 
 as a result of credit restricting (Braverman and Guasch, 
 1989) are some of the factors accused to be responsible 
 for the poor performance of the government-directed 
 credit big plans/layouts/dishonest plans in many countries. 
 With the sad/bad picture of state-owned (away from cities) finance 
 organisations, non-governmental micro-finance institutions have been growing to meet the credit needs of 
 small producers in many countries. Reports point to/show 
 that they now meet the credit demand of 10-12 million people in Africa, Asia and Latin America. 5 Many 
 of these organisations are give money tod not for soaking up high loan default costs but for covering high transaction costs connected with group-based lending and 
 other social intermediation costs (Khandker, 1988). If 
 farming-based credit and other targeted big plans/layouts/dishonest plans are to be 
 supported, policy makers must know how much they 
 are give money tod, who receives this helping payment, and whether 
 it helps the borrowers. 
 Testing the net (thing that's given/work that's done) of a program means 
 testing both its costs and benefits. Testing the 
 costs of lending involves the credited market cost of 
 the helping payment these big plans/layouts/dishonest plans receive from the government and (people who give money or other things). Testing benefits is often filled with problems because money is exchangeable and it is not clear if 
 3 Some studies, however, question the too much/too many interest rates of 
 informal lenders (e.g. Hussain and Demaine, 1992). 
 4 To reduce the moral danger-related problem and connected transaction costs of lending, banks often ask for physical 
 money. Money restrictions leave out/keep out the poor who do not have 
 valuable things, such as land, to offer as money but are otherwise good 
 credit risks. 
 5 For a discussion of a broad range of programs, see Otero and 
 Rhyne (1994), Name et al. (1994), Brugger and Rajpatirana 
 (1995), and Hulme and Mosley (1996). 
 
 the measured credit effect reflects the borrowing restriction or the unobservable (features/ qualities/ traits) of a borrower. The presence of bias caused by self-selection of 
 borrowers into credit programs may bias test 
 of benefits of these programs by as much as 100%. 6 
 Anyway, there are some studies that have 
 successfully guessed program benefits (Binswanger 
 and Khandker, 1995; Carter, 1988; Carter and Weihe, 
 1990; Feder et al., 1990; Pitt and Khandker, 1996, 
 1998). Binswanger and Khandker (1995) guessed the 
 hit/effect of formal credit using district-level panel data 
 from India and found that formal credit increases (away from cities) income and working well, and that benefits go beyond 
 the cost of the formal system by at least 13%. Feder 
 et al. (1990) guessed a switching moving backward model 
 for families in China and told the difference between 
 families that are credit-held back and those that 
 are not. 
 Pitt and Khandker (1998) examined the hit/effect of 
 credit from the Grameen Bank and other two targeted credit programs in Bangladesh on a variety of 
 individual and household results, including school 
 enrolment, labour supply, valuable thing holding, life-creating ability and 
 (device or drug that prevents pregnancy) use. They found credit to be a significant 
 (thing that decides something) of many household results, and 
 that program credit has a significant effect on 
 the well-being of poor families in Bangladesh. 
 Khandker (1988) watched/followed that micro-credit programs 
 are as (producing a lot for a given amount of money) as other programs, such as the 
 food for work, in benefiting the poor. 
 The goal of this paper is to analyse the role 
 of the Farming-based Development Bank of Pakistan 
 (ADBP) in areas away from cities and test its (producing a lot for a given amount of money)ness 
 in delivering farm credit. The paper's (thing that's given/work that's done) lies in adding to the existing books on the 
 (producing a lot for a given amount of money)ness of a government-supported farm 
 credit program which has not been managed well 
 for years. The data used in this paper's analysis 
 are drawn from the (away from cities) (money-related) Market Studies 
 (RFMS) of Pakistan. Results suggest that the effect 
 of ADBP finance is big, and that the hit/effect 
 is higher for smallholders than for medium and large 
 holders in farming. But, given the distribution of 
 loans and loan recovery rates, ADBPs lending program is not (producing a lot for a given amount of money). The program can be made 
 (producing a lot for a given amount of money) by supporting smallholders (who own 
