 up to 2.5 areas of land of land) more than medium and large 
 holders, by improving both loan recovery and (related to managing and running a company or organization) (wasting very little while working or producing something), and by making operations responsible 
 to a lending (mix of stocks, bonds, etc./document collection).? 
 The paper is organised as follows. Section 2 describes the survey and sample data used for the study. 
 Section 3 describes the (away from cities) credit market in Pakistan. Some studies including recent data show 
 that the (your share of sales out of all sales) of institutional credit is low (even though there is the existence of) government helping action since 1960. Also, formal credit has did not reach the borrowers who may 
 be able to use credit more productively. Section 4 explains the econometric model used to asses the credit 
 hits/effects on different household results. Section 5 
 discusses the moving backward results. Based on two-stage 
 guess ways of doing things, formal credit is found to have 
 significant good effects on most household results thought about/believed in this paper. Section 6 shows how 
 much social costs are involved for ADBP in providing credit. Section 7 presents the cost-benefit analysis 
 of the ADBP. The ending/deciding section summarises the 
 findings and discusses policy options. 
 
 2. Data 
 Data from the RFMS, collected for the State Bank 
 of Pakistan with (money-related) help from the World 
 Bank in 1996, are used. Household survey and informal lenders' survey data were collected by two 
 organisations: (1) the Applied Money-based Research 
 Centre (AERC, 1998) of the University of Karachi 
 and (2) the Punjab Money-based Research Institute 
 (PERI) in Lahore. The Pakistan Institute of Development Money flow (PIDE) in Islamabad collected 
 the institutional data on the ADBP and commercial 
 banks working in the (away from cities) part/area. Household survey 
 data were collected for all five areas of Pakistan, 
 namely, north western edge of something/unexplored area area of control/area of land (NWFP), 
 Sindh, Balochistan, Punjab and Pakistan controlled 
 Kashmir (AJ&amp;K). A (away from cities) household survey was 
 conducted on the pattern of the LSMS surveys managed and did/done by the World Bank to provide the data base. 
 7 By providing more loans to smallholders, transaction costs 
 may increase but loan default costs will decrease, because the loan 
 recovery rates are higher for smallholders than for large holders 
 in farming. 
 
 The survey covered different parts of the household 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things), including (information about the numbers of different kinds of people), labour 
 supply, household expense, income sources, farm 
 production, borrowing practices, valuable things and (things you owe/things you're responsible for/disadvantages). 
 A two-stage layered sampling plan was 
 put into use for selection of villages and families. In the 
 first stage, 250 villages were selected randomly from 
 a total of about 50,000 villages in Pakistan 
 (as reported in Farming-based Statistics, 1994-1995). 
 The portion of villages within the areas was 
 done in proportion to (helped to grow) area. A completely 
 randomised sampling plan was put into use for each 
 (related to a local area) sample. Villages were selected randomly 
 from the area of control/area of land after leaving out/keeping out very small and very 
 large villages, depending on the size distribution of 
 villages within each area of control/area of land. 
 In the second stage, household information from 
 each village was used to sample families on the 
 basis of landholding size and/or (related to working on the job) distribution. A (official count of everyone who lives in a country, city, etc.)  of families was done in each of 
 the selected 250 villages to gather information on landholding size and (related to working on the job) distribution. To sample 
 families within a village, a three-stage procedure 
 was adopted. First, the number of families selected 
 from a village was in proportion to the total household counts of villages. Second, the distribution of the 
 families drawn from a village was in proportion to 
 the distribution of landholding categories. Finally, the 
 families to be interviewed were drawn randomly 
 from the total number of families in each category 
 in each village. In all, the survey covered 6000 families from the 250 selected villages, for an average of 
 24 families per village. However, because of data 
 collection errors, we finally managed to use data on 
 4380 families from 217 villages in this paper. In order to reflect the actual distribution, we used sampling 
