 Our data collection plan was such that we collected consumption and other information for the last 
 reference farming-based year (1995/1996), while information collected on loans referred to the 5 years coming before the survey. Table 2 presents the distribution of 
 sample families (4380) by loan categories. A total 
 of 2581 families (that is, 59%) were reported to 
 borrow from any source over the 5 year period. A total of 180 families borrowed from formal sources. 
 Out of these families, 91 also borrowed from informal sources. Table 2 also shows the distribution of 
 borrowing status by area of control/area of land. As Punjab has by far 
 the largest population (55% of families sampled 
 were from Punjab), it is no wonder it has the highest 
 percentage of borrowing families (51%). Although 
 families borrowing from formal sources represent 
 only 7% of all borrowing families, formal sources 
 account for 21.9% of total loan amount/quantity, because the 
 average size of formal loans is much larger than that of 
 informal loans (Table 3). This means informal sources 
 still account for 78% of the loan volume in (away from cities) Pakistan. However, the share of formal credit has been 
 increasing slowly and regularly (PACC, 1973, 
 1985, 1995). 
