 The data show that formal credit is meant mostly 
 for production and investment, while informal credit 
 is mostly for eating/drinking smoothing. As Table 4 
 shows, only 5.2% of formal loan amount/quantity, compared 
 with 55.5% of informal loan volume, went to meet 
 consumption and other personal needs. However, 
 informal loans are given mostly for shorter periods 
 (77.5% of them are for a length of time of l year or less), 
 while formal loans are mostly long-term (76.7% are 
 for more than a year). More importantly, formal credit 
 goes almost completely to support farming-based production (87.5%), while only 26.9% of informal loans 
 support farming. Past studies also have shown that 
 formal credit adds/gives significantly to farming 
 of (away from cities) Pakistan (Zuberi, 1989; Malik et al., 1991). 
 Zuberi (1989) finds that 70% of total formal credit is 
 used to buy seed and fertiliser. 
 The issue now is to what extent formal credit matters to agriculture. Zuberi (1989) ends/decides that most 
 of the increases in farming-based output can be explained 
 by changes in the amount of seed and fertiliser expense. Malik et al. ( 1991) tries to provide (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) 
 for the role of formal credit in farming-based produc- 
 
 tion. They use a two-stage structure in which the chance of taking a formal loan is (described the future) in the 
 first stage and the (described the future) value is used in the second stage to guess the hit/effect of fertiliser use per 
 area of land. 9 Like Zuberi's study (1989), their results show 
 that formal credit is an important (thing that decides something) of fertiliser and seed expense. The study of von Braun 
 et al. (1993) shows that farmers with access to credit 
 have 37% higher input expenses than those without such access. 
 The hit/effect of credit in farming, however, depends on who receives formal loans. Our survey data 
 shows that, families with large operational holding (more than 25 areas of land), who are about 4.1% of 
 all families, account for 41.6% of all families 
 borrowing only from formal sources (Table 5). 
 In contrast, families with no operational holding, 
