 One possible way of resolving the endogeneity of 
 credit is to decide/figure out whether there is any (coming from the outside of something) (ability to be picked/ability to participate) judging requirements used by lenders in selecting 
 borrowers. Such an (ability to be picked/ability to participate) rule was used by Pitt 
 and Khandker (1998) to sort out the endogeneity of 
 credit received/got from micro-credit programs such as 
 the Grameen Bank. They used a almost-experimental 
 survey design as an identification plan in a setting where (able to be picked/able to participate) and non-(able to be picked/able to participate) families based 
 on landholding were interviewed in both program and 
 control areas. Such an (ability to be picked/ability to participate)-based instrumentation is not appropriate for testing the hits/effects of 
 ADBP loans, since the ADBP has no (coming from the outside of something) loan 
 (ability to be picked/ability to participate) judging requirements. 
 Finding convincing tests/lists of questions (Zij (numbers that change/things that change)) is 
 therefore a critical part of this exercise. According to 
 demand explanation, the price can be a good instrument 
 for (describing the future) the demand for a good. The price of an 
 ADBP loan is its interest rate, which hardly differs/changes. 
 Hence, the interest rate cannot be a good (describe the future)or 
 of the demand for credit. We propose a set of (tools or objects used to do work or measure something) based on the idea (you think is true) that the loanable 
 fund of the ADBP is fixed and the demand for ADBP 
 loans is much larger. More than that, the ADBP pays 
 much more than what it gets ready as savings and its 
 loanable money mostly come from the government and 
 (people who give money or other things). In this case, it is not the price of a loan but 
 the availability of the fund that matters most in deciding/figuring out how much a household can borrow from the 
 ADBP. That brings us to the loan portion organization 
 of ADBP money based on the competition among borrowers. ADBP money is first gave out at the area of control/area of land 
 level, then at the district level, and then at village 
 level before they are finally paid to borrowing 
 families. At the district level certain districts are 
 preferred to others based on certain judging requirements and portions are made to those districts. In those districts 
 again, certain villages are preferred to others and money 
 are made available to those villages in the same way/in that way. Finally money is paid to certain families based 
 on their qualifications. So these money is subject to 
 competition at each level and the final payment 
 is the total amount of result of all competitions. 
 So given the available money, a household's borrowing from the ADBP depends not only on its own 
 
