 The Durbin-Wu-Hausman test simply tests the importance of the 
 leftover/extra value that is (described the future) in the first stage moving backward and 
 included in the second stage moving backward. 
 
 To decide/figure out whether 2SLS (where endogeneity is 
 controlled using the competitors' (features/ qualities/ traits) as (tools or objects used to do work or measure something)) is more appropriate than OLS, we carried 
 out the Durbin-Wu-Hausman (DWH) test, which basically calculates an F-statistic for the leftover/extra term 
 that is (described the future) from the first stage Eq. (2a) and then 
 used as an explanatory (number or thing that changes) in the second stage 
 Eq. (1). 14 Table 9 reports the test results. They show 
 that in four out of six results there are planned 
 differences between the two models. This means in 
 these cases, the OLS results show that the amount of 
 credit from formal sources cannot be taken as given, 
 and it responds to the same (numbers that change/things that change) that affect the 
 results of interest. Because of this, the two-stage guesses 
 are preferred over the OLS guesses. 
 14 The second stage equation uses both the credit (number or thing that changes) and 
 the (described the future) leftover/extra as explanatory (numbers that change/things that change). 
 
 The two-stage guesses reported in Table 8 measure the response ability to stretch of result with respect 
 to borrowing from the ADBP. They show/tell about that ADBP 
 credit improves/increases household per person 
 consumption, for example. So, a 10% increase in 
 borrowing increases consumption by 0.04% for formal loans. Formal credit also increases crop production expenses of (away from cities) families. One major purpose 
 of credit is to support production costs such as hiring labour or buying fertiliser and other inputs. A 
 10% increase in borrowing from the ADBP increases 
 farming-based production costs by about 1%. 
 The effect of ADBP credit on the net value of farming-based production (i.e. gross value of production less 
 changeable production cost) is positive and significant. 
 A 10% increase in borrowing from a formal source 
 increases farming-based production by almost by 1%. 
 ADBP loans also increase female labour supply, without having any significant effect on male labour supply. The ability to stretch of the response of female labour 
 supply with respect to formal credit is 0.098, suggesting that a 10% increase in formal lending is related to about a 1% increase in female labour 
 supply. 
