 6. The AD BPs cost of lending 
 How much does it cost the ADBP to lend to the 
 farming community in Pakistan? The costs of and benefits (income) from lending by a formal lender such 
 as the ADBP are based on the costs of lending and 
 interest income came/coming from lending. In addition to 
 lending, investment and other businesses that a bank 
 begins/tries can create income. These can be found 
 in the bank's once-a-year report which provides a statement of income and expense from its activities. 
 However, the once-a-year report of the ADBP does not 
 reflect the true cost of its activities. For example, it 
 receives give money tod money from the government and 
 (people who give money or other things), and the once-a-year report does not reflect the opportunity cost of such money (PIDE, 1998). In order 
 to test ADBPs true cost of lending, we must account for the payments it receives since these payments come at a cost to the government and the (community of people/all good people in the world). 
 Since an (very big/very strong) part of/amount of the formal loans 
 comes from the ADBP (86.5% as shown in Table 3), 
 the cost of (that is, the net helping payment gave/given to) the 
 ADBP can be used to represent the costs of formal 
 lenders. 
 The payments to the ADBP come from interest-free 
 grants and givebackary money (that are received/got at 
 below-market interest rates). The helping payment from givebackal money is defined as the difference between 
 the market interest rate (which is the opportunity cost 
 of the give money tod money) and the actual interest rate 
 times the total value of the money. Since no interest 
 is charged on grants, the helping payment from grants is the 
 market interest rate times the grant amount. The total helping payment gave/given to the ADBP is the sum of these 
 
 207 
 
 two payments plus equity helping payment calculated from once-a-year equity. The net helping payment is the helping payment after the 
 (money made/good thing received) is netted out. As Table ll shows, the net helping payment of ADBP increased from 1685 million rupees in 
 1991 to 3312 million rupees in 1995 (Qureshi et al., 
 1999). This increase was due to the increase in borrowing money and equity that happened while interest 
 rates remained mostly constant. The average helping payment 
 was 4.7% of the loans outstanding in 1991 and 7.5% 
 in 1995. 15 
 The (in name only/very small amount) interest rate of ADBP loans increased 
 (a) little from 1991 to 1995 and from 12.5 to 13.5%. 
 The rate of inflation during this period increased from 
 9.6% in 1991 to 13.9% in 1993, and then decreased to 
 10.4% in 1995. The data clearly show that the real rate 
 of interest on an ADBP loan was negative for most of 
 the time during the study period. So one way of reducing the helping payment dependence of the ADBP would be to 
 increase the (in name only/very small amount) interest rate it changes. To decide/figure out how much the (in name only/very small amount) rate of interest would 
 have to be increased to eliminate the helping payment, we use 
 the helping payment dependence index (SDI) measure (Yaron, 
 1992). The SDI is expressed as the net helping payment (total 
 helping payment less accounting (money made/good thing received)) as a percentage of interest income received from on-lending (which is in tum 
 defined as the average loan outstanding times the (in name only/very small amount) interest rate). The SDI measures the percentage increase in the average on-lending interest rate needed/demanded 
 to eliminate all payments in a given year while keeping the return on equity equal to the non-giveback 
 borrowing cost. Between 1991 and 1995, the SDI increased from 0.38 to 0.56. So, in order to eliminate 
 helping payment it receives, the ADBP would have had to increase the on-lending interest rate by 38% in 1991 
 and by 56% in 1995. Using the (in name only/very small amount) rate for those 
 years, this means that the (in name only/very small amount) rate should have 
 increased from 12.5 to 17.2% in 1991 and from 13.5 
 to 21% in 1995. 
 Another way of reducing helping payment dependence is to 
 improve the loan recovery rate. Loan recovery has 
 been a major concern for all government-run credit 
 
 15 The helping payment gave/given to the ADBP is similar with that 
 of other successful banks around the world. For 
 example, the Grameen Bank of Bangladesh, which is a role model 
 for micro-credit programs worldwide, enjoyed a helping payment rate of 
 5.6% in 1994 (Khandker, 1988). But unlike the Grameen Bank, 
 ADBP loans are received mostly by large landholders. 
 
